{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a38156b-be44-4725-a7c4-3de72866d899","content":"\n\nIn .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class and subscribe to them:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`, and `OnResumed()` directly.\n\nFor **platform-specific** hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.OnResignActivation(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Quick mapping:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7cd9cbcd-2262-41cf-bfe9-73ed169cf639","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. Instead of those virtual methods on `Application`, you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class.\n\nSpecifically:\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated`\n\n\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped` events\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` or `Window.Activated` events\n\nThe most practical approach is to either override `CreateWindow()` in your `App` class to hook into window lifecycle events, or create a custom `Window` subclass where you can override the lifecycle methods directly.","outputTokens":679},"id":"bc2a49b0-2321-406e-9ee9-a71c29d7680b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:10.502Z","parentId":"6b89e337-a293-4449-9a15-7eca5b9e7a13"}
